'''Koushinsha''' (こうしんしゃ) is a shrine located in {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nogata City|ja|直方市|12=draft}}, in the Yamabe area<ref>もと{{ill|Kurate District|ja|鞍手郡|12=draft}} {{ill|Yamabe Village|ja|山部村 (福岡県)|12=draft}}</ref>. It is a shrine that enshrines deities in a syncretic (【神仏習合】) tradition.

Within the shrine grounds, stone-carved figures of monkeys—linking the character "申" in "Koushin" with the "猿" (monkey) of {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|猿田彦大神|12=draft}}—are believed to represent the "Mitsushi" (three corpses) theory of {{ill|Koushin faith|ja|庚申信仰|12=draft}}, such as the "see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil" concept, with several hundred carved "saru" present.

== Worshipped Deities (Saijin) ==
{{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|12=draft}}}}
* In {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft}}, the deity is {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|猿田彦大神|12=draft}}.
* In {{ill|Buddhism|ja|仏教|12=draft}}, the deity is {{ill|Seimen Kongō|ja|青面金剛|12=draft}}.

== History (Yūshi) ==
With {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|猿田彦大神|12=draft}} as the principal deity, the shrine was transferred to its present location from the Koushin Shrine in {{ill|Karatsu|ja|唐津市|12=draft}} in February of Genbun 2 (1737).

== Festivals and Events ==
[[File:Koushin002.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Three monkeys]]
* December 5: Annual Grand Festival
* August 5: Natsugoe Festival
* Every month on the 5th: A monthly festival is held (since 1959, a large sale event called "Itsukaichi" has been organized in the central shopping district of Nogata, capitalizing on the divine virtues).

== Location and Transportation ==
: {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|12=draft}} Nogata City, Yamabe 601
* A 10‑minute walk from {{ill|JR Nogata Station|ja|直方駅|12=draft}}.

